segments.text: Okay, we're talking about the MetroCom system.
We will be expanding our database to incorporate all the demographic information that we need for the city, integrate the census data, the dime file.
Two things that we do here that are very important that require our use of the computer.

is we're responsible for the council districts and redistricting our city charter requires that we redistrict every time that we annex and so and at least every election year and of course every two years we have to do redistricting or at least evaluate the city for redistricting and then we're responsible for the annexations so that we have to do studies on both areas and the computer will help us quite a bit
The Texas laws regarding annexation are, I understand, pretty good compared to some states.

and i gather that's helped houston in the past in terms of its suburbs and the suburban growth wanted to incorporate and taking advantage of the city's resources without paying taxes to the city yes i think probably we have the best set of annexation laws in the country from a municipality's point of view and at this last session of the legislature we had to
beat back about three attempts to reduce our authority in the extraterritorial jurisdiction and our annexation authority.
For example, there was a proposal to have the citizens vote before they could be annexed.
There was another proposal that we had to announce annexations a year and another two years ahead of time.
So all those things we finally were able to defeat.
Now, Ephraim, can we
Now I'll turn to the major effort of the department, the major new effort, which is the comprehensive plan that has received so much recent publicity.
Can you describe how this effort came into being?
Who is responsible for pushing for a comprehensive plan?
And what the goal of the plan is?
And is it going to be a long-range,
general plan for development of the city?
Or is it going to be different than what we think of as the classical model of a comprehensive plan?
Well, we have developed a Houston solution to the planning process.
And it took me about six months after I arrived here to develop the methodology by which we could do
a comprehensive plan for the city of Houston.
And it will not be a comprehensive plan in the traditional sense.
The need for a planning document is evident.
The old, the term that I keep repeating time and time again is in the past, Houston has reacted to growth and now we're going to begin to plan for growth.
Because of our lack of land use controls,
it is very difficult to come up with a comprehensive plan that would then be implementable.
So what we have developed is a different approach and use public improvements as the carrot to bring about growth as we would like to see it occur.
So that the planning process is going to feed right into our
CAPITAL IMPROVEMENTS PLAN.

AND IN THAT FASHION, WITH THE PLAN CONTROLLING WHERE THE CAPITAL IMPROVEMENTS ARE GOING TO GO, THEN WE THINK THAT THE CAPITAL IMPROVEMENTS WOULD EVENTUALLY, ONCE WE HAVE CAUGHT UP WITH OUR BACKLOG AND WE'RE BEHIND TIMES IN IMPROVEMENTS, BUT WE THINK BY 1994 WE WILL BE CAUGHT UP.
WE WILL THEN BE ABLE TO BEGIN TO CONSTRUCT FACILITIES AND PROJECT
where growth is going to occur and construct the support system for that growth.
And once that support system exists, then it should attract the growth into those areas.
That's seven years away.
Yes, it's seven years away.
We have a capital improvements plan now that covers us through 1992, a five-year capital improvements plan.
And we think the planning process we're embarking on now will take us at least four years.
So that the situation that we find ourselves in is this, that not only are we planning for Houston and the 600 square miles of Houston, but also the 1,400 square miles of UTJ.
How do you relate to HGAC on this?
There is the only interaction that we have with HGAC has to do with transportation planning because they are the transportation group for the area.
And so we work with them on major transportation improvements, et cetera.
But other than that, the HGAC and the other, there's one other area that we interrelate, and that is in population estimation.
We have formed one central group here, a central task force, under the coordination of HGAC to develop all growth estimates.
And so that metro, the city, all the utilities,
HGAC, everyone is using the same population projection.
Well, in that respect, you have diverged from state government.
They use two.

So what I was trying to do is come up recognizing that starting from point zero and trying to plan 2,000 square miles, which is an area larger than the state of Delaware, as the planning magazine said last time,
I thought that the traditional concept of preparing a comprehensive plan for the entire area and then implement smaller segments of it into neighborhood plans and smaller areas was not feasible.
From taking the overall look first and then coming down into more specific areas.
So in effect, we're going to do it the opposite way.
We have developed, first of all,
As you can imagine, in 2,000 square miles, there are many separate characteristics in the various areas.
And so we've developed two major characteristics that we're going to deal with.
One is the inner city neighborhoods, and one is what we would consider stable neighborhoods and growth areas.
And so we've divided our planning system into something that we call neighborhood planning and sector planning.
Because went through that.
So you understand the difference between the two techniques.
Right.
And so that right now, we're looking at 25 neighborhood plans and 23 sector plans.
And then we will begin to aggregate them first into quadrant plans and eventually into what I guess you could call a comprehensive plan.
But I would more likely call an executive summary, a summary of what we find in these 48 documents.

And these documents are going to be rather substantial documents because they will contain everything on that neighborhood, including a projection as to what public improvements are going to be required over a 10 or at least a 10-year period in the future.
And so that is the process we're embarking in.
We're ensuring, first of all, that there is coordination by implementing what we call a staff task force that not only includes

the various departments of the city, but also the many other multiple agencies, the Harris County Flood Control District, the Turnpike Authority, the school districts, Metro, all the other agencies that would have some input into the planning process.
And the big task force is they will have a specific assignment, and they will be
sun-setted automatically when they finish the task.

Yes, when the planning process is complete, we would expect these task forces to basically run out of work, although there will be an update process that will continue to go on, and we may have some need for at least a staff task force.
The other task force that we're creating is what we call a TAC, T-A-C, the Technical Advisory Committee, and that provides the input from the outside
the government, etc.

We have representatives of all the major organizations, American Institute of Architects, American Planning Association, Apartment Association, the Builders Association, BOMA, the Building Owners and Managers Association, NAIOP, National Association of Office and Industrial Parks, all these various special interest groups form a technical advisory committee
that will also provide us some input into the plans.
That is neighborhoods.
The neighborhoods will be represented in two ways.

Our technical advisory committee contains overall citywide neighborhood representation, plus there will be local representatives of specific neighborhoods when covering their specific area when it's being planned.
Is there any formal procedure for the selection of those people?
The Planning Policy Manual, which has been approved by the Planning Commission, establishes the composition of the organizations that would be represented.
We merely ask the organizations then to give us their representatives.
We ask for a representative and two alternates.
And so yesterday, for example, we met with the staff task force and the TAC.
We had over 100 people here.
And we briefed them on
the process, so they understand the process and what their role will be in this process.
Good luck.
Well...
It sounds like a monumental job.
I think it's a major undertaking and
We have received the support of every major organization in the city except one.
The Houston Board of Realtors has refused to support the process even though they have provided members to the TAC.
They did want to be represented for the TAC.
But every other organization, the Chamber of Commerce, the Builders Association, Pardon Association, all these groups have chosen to support the process.
So we feel that that's a big step already in assuring that it's going to happen.
How did this...
project gap started?
Who pressed the start button for it?
Well, of course, when I arrived here, the mayor gave me three major tasks he wanted me to accomplish.
One was to initiate a planning process, but she didn't define what planning process.
Two, the initiation of revitalization in the inner city.
And three was to initiate public-private partnerships.
throughout the city.
Up until now, the city, or up until then, the city and the building community and the development community had basically been antagonists.
And the idea was to keep the city down as ineffective as possible in controlling what was happening.
She wanted partnerships to be established.
And so in implementing the planning side of it,

I began to try and devise a method by which we could eventually get to a comprehensive plan, recognizing that without land use controls, the traditional planning system where you develop a comprehensive plan, which is then implemented by a zoning plan or something like that, was impossible.
So we have looked at this opposite approach of using the public improvements.
And the CIP process says that projects that
appear on the comprehensive plan will be given priority over other projects.

So it gives us a mechanism by which people have now come forward and want to participate in the process because they want their particular areas to be included and receive their fair share of improvements.
Ephraim, in the private sector, has there been any discussion about the use of performance standards rather than zoning?
Yes, we've had a lot of discussions.
Two particular groups that are working on these.
As we do the master plans that we're talking about, the comprehensive plans, one of the planning areas that we're going to do in the sector is going to be the downtown.
Now, this sector plan has the full support of the private sector.
and particularly of an organization called Central Houston Incorporated.
Bob Urie is the head of it, which is the organization of all the major property owners and corporations downtown.

And so the big question that has come up in that area, plus the Galleria area where a planning process is also going to be done, is how are we going to ensure that, what incentives can we give to people to,

assure ourselves that they would follow the plan well the answer is right now you don't can't give any because any uh incentives because right now you don't have any controls so therefore there can be no incentives so they have already initiated a study in working with this department on the full range of development controls that are used in other cities

all the way from the San Francisco-New York controls to the performance-type controls, with the idea of what is the national standard right now, or state of the art, and began to look at it from those areas.
We are embarking already on our first major effort on an off-street parking ordinance.
Off-street parking right now seems kind of innocuous in that
Most cities have included that in their zoning ordinance or some other thing.

But we're looking at it as a major way of controlling land use because what is going to happen, particularly in the older areas of the city, the residential areas, without deed restrictions, where someone could come in and just take a residence and convert it to a restaurant, for example, or office space.
Now our off-street parking ordinance is going to say, well, if you're going to run a restaurant there,
you're going to have to provide an off-street parking space for every four seats.
Or if you're going to want an office, you need an off-street parking space for each 200 square feet of office space.
So now that person just can't come in and take a house in the middle of the road and convert it to that because he won't have the adequate parking.
And so in effect, then we have limited the use of that space to a space that can
meet the off-street parking requirements, which is probably going to be residential, because we only require two off-street parking spaces for residents.
So that will begin to control parking.
In the modern buildings in Houston, parking is not a problem, because lenders have controlled that.
And we find that most buildings either meet or exceed ULI standards.

But it'll be in the older areas of the city where we're getting the complaints about restaurants moving into neighborhoods, clubs, so forth, and creating parking problems for the residents because the streets will be full of the clients.
And so off-street parking ordinance by itself will begin to correct some of these things.
But we look at a series of controls that will
be basically based along the line of performance zoning.
Okay.
Then the procedure will, of course, follow standard state law procedure in terms of adoption.
Yes.
I'm going to mention something, is that Houston has a whole body of law
that applies only to Houston.
State law.
State law that applies only to Houston and recognizes our unique position as being unzoned.

For example, we have been able to get extensive legislation on deed restrictions, a reinstatement of deed restrictions, extension of deed restrictions, initiation of new deed restrictions, all made a matter of state law so that you can use those mechanisms to control land use.
Also, we didn't have any development controls in legal form until 1983.
Prior to that time, all standards for plant development, plant preparation, just existed as policies of the department and had no legal basis.
In 1983, when the city passed its development ordinance, we were confronted with a situation that anything prior to 1983 was basically grandfathered.
If you didn't need to subdivide to construct something,
You were grandfathered.
And so we developed what we called a development plan.
And that was a plan that would be used in those instances where you needed a building permit, but a subdivision plan was not appropriate according to state law.
And you had a 25-acre tract of land, and you were going to build a shopping center.
Under state law, you don't have to submit a subdivision plan because you're not dividing land.
Therefore, the development could proceed without oversight of the planning commission.

Well, we developed a development plan in Houston that any time that you are building a new building or modifying an existing building such as you enlarge its size, its footprint, you then have to submit a development plan that will bring you under the new controls.
And in 1985, we had the development plan concept codified under state law
as applicable only to Houston.

And in 1987, the current session of legislature, we went one step further and gave it a development plan, the same recognition as a subdivision plan, for the dedication of right of way, for filing in the county clerk's office, et cetera.
So now we have two types of plans in Houston.
And that's something peculiar to Houston, but meets the need that we have here of bringing in all development that occurred before 1983 under our current controls.
In working through your sector plans, you mentioned that this will be coordinated by a task force, or that it will be assisted by a task force.
Yes.
It will be functionally oriented people, experts.
But you'll also, I presume, have a regular planning staff person.

assigned to each of these sectors as they move through to their own development plans to coordinate it with the central office here so that they can be provided with advice regarding any overall considerations that the planning department has for that particular area of the city so that you won't be handed something that you can't use.
No.
Actually, we will prepare the plans here.
The neighborhood planning process is going to be handled by our neighborhood planning division.
The sector planning process is going to be handled by the comprehensive planning division.
I see.
Who's heading up the neighborhood planning division now?
Paulette Wagner.
I think that's the person that Roberta told you to interview.
Yes.
Okay.
Okay.
And so in each of those divisions, there are planners assigned in such numbers that we can assign a planner to each plan.
And that planner then will have the responsibility of carrying that plan all the way through.
The task force and the technical advisory committee
are there to review his work and provide him information, ensure that we're not committing, for example, Harris County flood control to something that they don't plan to do.
We have a water plan, master water plan, master wastewater plan, ensure that these technical people understand what's going in the plan and that we can accomplish what the plan will call for.
We want this to be a plan that is
When we develop a 10-year strategy or a year 2000 strategy, that the things that are going to this plan will be doable in that period of time.
And so to a certain extent, these plans are going to be proactive plans because we've had the participation and the cooperation of all these various city departments.
They will then know what the plan calls for their departments to do.
And we would then expect them to be able to carry out what the plan commits them to do.
If they don't have the ability of doing it,
then they need to tell us at the planning stage so that we can iron that out.
And you say that this process will probably take five years?
Well, we're talking about a four-year process.

Individual plans will probably take us about eight months each to do because there are three public hearings set up and a process by which eventually the city council will approve each plan to ensure that everyone recognizes that this is an official process.
official plan.
Will these be adopted separately by the Council?
Yes, they will be adopted separately and the Planning Commission will adopt them separately and refer them to City Council.
Will they be published separately?
Yes, we're calling our operation the Compendium of Plans.
So we figured that we're going to have a library that's going to have 51 documents.
Almost one.
53 documents, isn't it?
One for each week of the year.
Yeah.
48 of these documents are going to be either neighborhood or sector plans, 23 sector and 25 neighborhoods.
Then we will have four quadrant summaries, and then we will have the overall summary.
And we're planning, for example, to distribute these by having people subscribe, like planning firms and development firms to subscribe so they would get the plans as they come off the assembly line
and uh and then we get them periodically and then we can also make them available individually bound so that specific neighborhoods can get copies of their own plan the uh
I believe right now with our staffing that we probably have the capability of doing four or five sector plans and four or five neighborhood plans simultaneously.
So even though the whole process will take us four years, there will be plans coming off the assembly line after eight months.
on a continuous basis during that period of time.
So it will be a gradual process.

And that's another reason for using this building block approach, is that we will have usable documents early in the process without having to wait five years before we had something that we could use.
Well, that's an advantage politically, I'm sure.
At the end of this, after everything has been adopted, then you're presumably in planner's heaven.
What will life be like after adoption of plans?
Well, one of the things we, particularly the sector plans, we figure are going to undergo considerable revision.
So we have set a biannual updating process.
Those sector plans that are in the high growth areas of the city will require revision.
All plans will be reviewed every two years.
I would imagine that the inner city plans are going to be relatively stable, but that those in rapid growth areas are going to be
subject to continuous flux, and so we will be updating them and keeping current with them.

Of course, we've already mentioned the new policy of, I guess it's an informal policy, of encouraging infilling into the older neighborhoods of Houston and greater attention to the needs of the commuter and metro and whatnot.
That's quite a change from what it has been in the past when potential is largely focused on the fringe growth areas.
Yes, we have a plan right now, our mobility plan, which is a gold document for mobility.
Establish goals for all the various agencies responsible for traffic and transportation within the city, the state highway department, the metro, the city.
And so right now, we're spending approximately $2 billion a year to improve traffic in Houston.
And the eventual goal of our program is traffic and the condition of traffic, instead of being
one of the black marks looked at when Houston is being considered.
It'll be one of the positive points.
And so we're proceeding with that.
There's construction underway now all over the city.
In its last bond issue, the city made a $600 million bond issue for public improvements, $400 million of which is going to streets.
So the highway department has commitments.
Every freeway in the city now is under construction or under expansion.
Metro is implementing their process of putting bus lanes in the middle of every freeway and high occupancy vehicle lanes, actually.
And so that we're seeing the light at the end of the tunnel, you might say, in that we're looking at the year 1994 when our system will be at capacity.
And everything we do after 1994
will be, and that's from a system that was operating at 175% capacity.
And that is, that would be the period in 1994 would be our break over point after which we will be building for projected growth rather than just
building as a result of overcapacity of the system.
Well, I've read horror stories about fires that have occurred in Houston, and there has not been enough water pressure to put them out.
There have been so many leaks in the water distribution system that the pressure is insufficient for the fire.
Well,
I think we have two major, well actually three major enterprise programs.
We call them enterprise funds in the city because those are funds that do not require money from the tax base.
One is water, one is wastewater, and the other is airports.
The water system right now, our master plan for water actually is
not directed towards the matter of pressure and capacity because most of the city now is receiving its full range of capacity.
Now, we do not have and do not meet the state standard of overhead water tanks to provide pressure in case of a power failure.
And that is a continuing problem we have with the Water Commission, that it would cost
multiple millions of dollars to build those tanks in order to have water.
Because the maximum altitude in Houston is 40 feet above sea level.
And so we can't, in order to provide gravity pressure, we would have to do it artificially.
So our entire system is based on pump pressure.
Now there are some neighborhoods where we're in the process of replacing lines to provide adequate pressure.
But under our current standards,

we require the distance between water mains and water pressure the city is basically overcome that problem that you indicated there are some areas in the city still particularly industrial areas along the waterfront that might be a little further than 200 feet that we normally require from a water from a fire main but as a whole the all new development and most of the older city now meets that standard now in the area of wastewater
We have embarked on another multi-billion dollar program to provide wastewater capacity.
And we are again looking at 1994 as a year in which we will be able to do away with all building controls as a result of lack of wastewater capacity.
And at the present time, there is considerable work going on.
As I say, it's a multi-billion dollar program, about $2.5 billion to bring us up to that capacity.
And as far as airports are concerned, we are expanding both Hobby and Intercontinental.
Ellington Air Force Base, which has been turned over to the city, is being converted into a general aviation airport.
And we've initiated the study for the West Airport, which would be a West commercial airport.
In the vicinity of Katy?
Yes, it'll go in this area here, which is between Brookshire and Katy.
This is the area for the airport, which the city has already bought.
They already own that land.
That'll be very handy for people from College Station.
Well, it'll be a lot closer going into Intercontinental.
Right now, going into Intercontinental from the north is almost impossible.
There doesn't seem to be any direct connection by road from Interstate 45 to the airport coming from the north.
Well, of course, eventually we're going to have the Grand Parkway.
And on the map behind you, you can see the track of the Grand Parkway, which is, yes, that heavy blue line coming across right there.
No, no, around.
It'll be a circle.
Go up, right there, go left now.
See that line?
Oh, yeah.
OK, that's the Grand Parkway.
And what it'll do, you'll be able to pick that off of 290 and then get on the Grand Parkway, and then come on around, and then get off and get down to the airport.
So you'll have the toll road coming straight south from there.
going by the airport.
It's the connection between Interstate 45 and the airport coming from the north at this time.
Well, see, between those two, we're now building the toll road, party toll road.
Right here.
Yeah.
And that's going to be able to bring you down, straight down, and that'll have an exit at the airport.
I hope it has a sign saying airport.
There is none now.
Absolutely none.
When you come from the north, there is no sign saying airport until you get way down south of the airport and then you have to take the lateral.
As a matter of interest, since you drive down from A&M all the time, you enter Houston ETJ when you leave the city limits of Prairie View.
Come on.
That's the limit of our ETJ.
That red line on that map is the ETJ.
We actually go further past Prairie View.
We just have to stop at the city limit.
You ran out of map.
Very interesting.
OK. An additional responsibility that we have is to maintain the extraterritorial jurisdiction and city limit agreements with 25 separate municipalities that impinge on the borders of Houston.
What we do is we trade off ETJs and make certain agreements.
For example, Hull Airport, which is outside Sugar Land, was in our ETJ.

Sugar Land desired to make that their municipal airport and wanted to spend municipal bonds to improve it, but they couldn't do it as long as it was in our ETJ because they would never be able to annex it.
So we agreed to trade Hull Airport to them.
But in return, we got ETJ back from Sugar Land that begins to surround Sugar Land, so that Sugar Land won't be able to grow.
We're now south of Sugar Land, all the way down to the Brazos River.
And so we've cut off Sugar Land from going to the south, so basically Sugar Land has become a fixed size.
Like Bel Air.
Yes.
And eventually, we'll be able to surround them with ETJ, and they won't be able to grow.
And of course, that was our purpose, to do that.
They needed the airport bad enough that they were willing to give up that authority.
But we trade all the time.
And we get involved in the creation of water districts and in monitoring the water districts.
We have responsibility for monitoring all 600
municipal utility districts in the Houston area.
On the map behind you, therefore, it says water districts.
You see all the water districts that surround the city.
The water district is our unit of land by which we annex, because we have to annex entire water districts.
And on that map you're looking at actually is our last annexation with respect to what water districts were involved.
We annexed about
13 square miles last year, about 25,000 population.
We are doing an orderly annexation.
We have what we call an aggressive annexation policy.

However, this year, because of two things, the great commitment of our enterprise funds, water and sewer, to meet existing needs and their inability to aggregate more debt, because we have to assume the debt of these utility districts.
And also the city's inability to assume more debt from a debt service perspective.
We limit our annexation only to very essential elements.
But we see that probably with the 1990 census, it will free us up under the Voter Voting Rights Act to be able to annex major areas like the 1960 area.
Because what we think that 1990 census will indicate is that our minority populations

in the central city will have grown to the extent that we will be able to annex the Anglos that live out in the 1960 area without altering the racial balance in the city that existed in 1965, which is a requirement of the act.
Very interesting.
I understand that HGAC has recently completed a regional waste disposal plan.

that has received uh has been received rather well and houston is participating in that yes we're looking very closely at resource recovery now there we have right now the city of houston does not have any landfills and it's not operating in landfills we contract with private companies it's a rather expensive uh proposition

Right now, as part of our CIP, we're looking at buying a site in Brazoria County, which is some 35 miles from the city, and which would involve a rather comprehensive transportation plan to get everything down there, because our city, our ETJ from end to end is 70 miles, so that you would take the far end, you might have 50 to 100 miles to go
with some of the waste.
And so therefore, we're looking at resource recovery, which would be a plant that would burn the garbage and trash, convert it to electricity, and also reduce the ash.
And the ash then would be transported by railroad car down to this landfill in Brazoria County.
And you'd have only one of these facilities?
Well, we're talking about building one, which would be a centralized one, a major one.
We don't have it built yet.
In the meantime, we're using BFI facilities.
But it's very difficult to place landfills with the growth that has occurred around Houston in any area which is accessible.
We have to go out considerable distances.
So what we do now is we have transfer stations
throughout the city where the trucks that do the initial pickup bring the stuff in, and then it's transferred to bigger trucks and then carted out to the landfills.
Well, it's a problem for cities all around the country now.
It's one of the major political headaches.
Well, that would be one of the reasons that I see this resource recovery plant as a major solution to our problem.
One of the things that happened is that we were in the process of getting it built.
by the private sector using the tax credits, et cetera, that were allowed under the law, the new tax bill eliminated most of those credits.
So now we're going to have to look at a different way of financing it.
And then glass would be treated separately to recover the oil.
Well, I've gone to see the one in Baltimore.
Baltimore has a state of the art.
And what they have a way of doing is they actually
recover a lot of the materials, metals and so forth, and use that also as a source of revenue.
But they just, in Baltimore, they just tip the garbage trucks right into the pit, and they burn everything.
Interesting.
There's no pre-separating.
Reminds me, when I lived in LA as a kid, we had to separate our glass and our cans from garbage.
We had three sacks.
for every pickup.
Everybody did it.
No one complained.
I think it's just what you get used to doing.
One of the things you look at is the caloric content of the mix.
And it has been found this system, for example, could be used in underdeveloped countries because the caloric mix of garbage there is different than American garbage.
But Baltimore has proved to be a
A very successful operation.
Ephraim, thanks very much for your time.
You'll receive a transcript of this whenever we can get around to doing it.
And I hope that you can return it more quickly than we can get the transcript to you.
Thanks very much.
OK.
